05607nam a22008415i 9781442623149DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161975onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013938791  a97814426231497 a10.3138/97814426231492doi  a(DE-B1597)465636  a(OCoLC)944178899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHM271b.D66 1975eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a301.15/52231 aKontos, Alkis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDomination /cAlkis Kontos. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©1975  a1 online resource (242 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tDominance in children -- tTowards a happier history: women and domination -- tDominion of capital: Canada and international investment -- tThe Third World: powerful or powerless? -- tLiberalism and the political theory of property -- tMerleau-Ponty: the ontological limitations of politics -- tDomination and history: notes on Jean-Paul Sartre’s -- tForm and metaphor in Fanon’s critique of racial and colonial domination -- tMagic and domination -- tOn science as domination -- tAlbert Camus’ Caligula: the metaphysics of an emperor -- tDomination: metaphor and political reality -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne is usually conscious of tyranny and oppression; domination is more subtle. It is an abandonment of our freedom, our will, and our love of justice, and yet socially, psychologically, and ontologically domination in some degree seems inevitable. There is now in the western world an uneasy sense that more domination is going on than necessary, and this work tries to outline the theoretic modalities of this human predicament. The twelve essays in Domination examine such questions as: Does the ego of the infant require for its development some experiences of dominance? Is it men or the system that causes the domination of women? How has capitalism with its property laws entailed limits on national and personal freedom? What do existentialism and critical theory have to tell us about violence and reason, or about magic and science, as modes of life that constrain everyone? What is racialism? And, if the world is beyond the powers of reason, what does modern man now make his public and private raison d’être? Those who are looking for amelioration of the quality and quantity of human freedom will find this book helpful in defining and cracking the chains. The contributors, in order of their appearance of their essays, are O. Weininger, Elizabeth Brady, R.T. Naylor, R.O. Matthews, C.B. Macpherson, Monika Langer, Keith McCallum, Ato Sekyi-Out, Christian Lenhardt, Ben Agger, David Cook, and Alkis Kontos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthority. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aSocial history. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aAgger, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKontos, Alkis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanger, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenhardt, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacpherson, C.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, R.O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCallum, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaylor, R.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct